\id 1TH - The English New Testament According to Family 35 
\h 1 Thessalonians 
\toc3 1 Th. 
\toc2 1 Thessalonians 
\toc1 The First Epistle of Paul to the Thessalonians 
\mt1 The First Epistle of Paul to the  
\mt1 THESSALONIANS  
\c 1  
\ms1 Opening Considerations  
\s1 Greeting  
\m
\v 1 \w Paul|strong="G3972"\w*, \w Silvanus|strong="G4610"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Timothy|strong="G5095"\w*,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Paul gives recognition to the junior members of the team.\f* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w congregation|strong="G1577"\w*\f + \fr 1:1 \ft The first image that the term ‘church’ evokes in the minds of many is that of a building; what is in view here is a group of people, and a very particular group of people.\f* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w Thessalonians|strong="G2331"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Sovereign \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*: \w Grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w peace|strong="G1515"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w from|strong="G1515"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Sovereign \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.\f + \fr 1:1 \ft To the ‘western’ mind the repetition of the full form, “God our Father and Sovereign Jesus Christ,” may seem unnecessary, if not stylistically poor, but this letter was written by a Hebrew. By switching from ‘the’ to ‘our’ Father he claims a personal relationship. Some 7.5% of the Greek manuscripts omit “from God our Father and Sovereign Jesus Christ” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*   
\s1 The Thessalonians are praised  
\p
\v 2 \w We|strong="G2249"\w* \w always|strong="G3842"\w* \w give|strong="G2168"\w* \w thanks|strong="G2168"\w* \w to|strong="G1909"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w for|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w making|strong="G4160"\w* \w mention|strong="G3417"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w in|strong="G1909"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w prayers|strong="G4335"\w*,  
\v 3 continually \w remembering|strong="G3421"\w* \w before|strong="G1715"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w your|strong="G2962"\w* \w work|strong="G2041"\w* \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2962"\w* \w labor|strong="G2873"\w* \w coming|strong="G2316"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* Love \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2962"\w* \w perseverance|strong="G5281"\w* based \w on|strong="G4102"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Hope|strong="G1680"\w*, \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* source,\f + \fr 1:3 \ft We are used to the rendering: ‘work of faith, labor of love, and patience of hope in our Lord Jesus Christ’. However, “faith”, “love”, “hope” and “Lord” all have the definite article and are in the genitive/ablative case. If we translate the definite articles it changes the ‘flavor’; we are looking at a particular faith, a particular love, a particular hope, and the three qualities either belong to the Lord or proceed from Him. The genitive/ablative case in Greek is quite ‘versatile’, and so just to render ‘of’ all the time is so ambiguous as to leave the precise intent undefined. (However, I can't guarantee that my attempt to ‘disambiguate’ is correct.)\f*  
\v 4 \w knowing|strong="G1492"\w* \w as|strong="G2316"\w* \w we|strong="G1492"\w* \w do|strong="G1492"\w*, brothers loved \w by|strong="G5259"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w chosen|strong="G1589"\w*.\f + \fr 1:4 \ft They are loved and chosen by God, marvelous privilege—verse 3 describes their appropriate response, which I suppose is how Paul ‘knew’ that they were chosen.\f*   
\s2 They became examples  
\p
\v 5 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w see|strong="G1492"\w*, \w our|strong="G2532"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w come|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w only|strong="G3440"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w power|strong="G1411"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*\f + \fr 1:5 \ft In verses 1 and 2 it is clear that the Father and the Son are distinct persons; here Paul adds the Holy Spirit.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* complete certainty\f + \fr 1:5 \ft Powerful manifestations of the Holy Spirit do have a way of adding certainty to the spoken word; they also help to face affliction with joy (next verse).\f* (\w of|strong="G3056"\w* course \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* sort \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w men|strong="G3588"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w proved|strong="G1096"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w be|strong="G1096"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w for|strong="G3754"\w* \w your|strong="G1223"\w* \w sake|strong="G1223"\w*).\f + \fr 1:5 \ft Why “for your sake”? They were giving an example to be followed.\f*  
\v 6 Yes \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w became|strong="G1096"\w* \w imitators|strong="G3402"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*,\f + \fr 1:6 \ft To imitate the messengers was to imitate the Lord; their walk with God presumably had something to do with the powerful manifestations.\f* \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w received|strong="G1209"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*'\w s|strong="G2962"\w* \w joy|strong="G5479"\w*,\f + \fr 1:6 \ft “The Holy Spirit's joy” in the soul is an unanswerable proof of the reality of true conversion; it also enables you to face “severe affliction” with equanimity.\f* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* spite \w of|strong="G3056"\w* severe \w affliction|strong="G2347"\w*,  
\v 7 \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w became|strong="G1096"\w* \w examples|strong="G5179"\w*\f + \fr 1:7 \ft They bought into the messengers' life style of total commitment to Christ and His Kingdom.\f* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w believers|strong="G4100"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Macedonia|strong="G3109"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Achaia.  
\v 8 \w That|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w sounded|strong="G2980"\w* \w out|strong="G1831"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w only|strong="G3440"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Macedonia|strong="G3109"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Achaia \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w place|strong="G5117"\w*\f + \fr 1:8 \ft For something to resound far and wide requires a sufficient cause. Their response to the Gospel was sufficiently vigorous that it caused widespread comment, comment about their transformed lives and the Message that could produce such transformation.\f*—\w your|strong="G2192"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w toward|strong="G4314"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w gone|strong="G1831"\w* \w forth|strong="G1831"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w need|strong="G5532"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w say|strong="G2980"\w* \w anything|strong="G5100"\w*.   
\s2 Their hope  
\p
\v 9 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* themselves report \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*\f + \fr 1:9 \ft Instead of “you”, perhaps 60% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘us’, as in most versions. I follow the best line of transmission.\f* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w kind|strong="G3697"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w entrance|strong="G1529"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w had|strong="G2192"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*,\f + \fr 1:9 \ft Paul did not have to ‘toot his own horn’.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w how|strong="G4459"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w turned|strong="G1994"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w idols|strong="G1497"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w slaves|strong="G1398"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w living|strong="G2198"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w true|strong="G3588"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*,  
\v 10 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* wait \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G2532"\w* \w Son|strong="G5207"\w* \it coming\it* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w heavens|strong="G3772"\w*\f + \fr 1:10 \ft Verses 9-10 give a good picture of true conversion. It involves turning your back on all the ‘idols’ that governed your life to trust in the true God; but the only acceptable way to truly relate to the Sovereign of the universe is as a slave = total commitment; this gives a valid hope for a bright future.\f* (\w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w raised|strong="G1453"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w among|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w dead|strong="G3498"\w*)\f + \fr 1:10 \ft Resurrection has to do with bodies (it is the body that is resurrected, to be reunited with the spirit), so the Son will return with a visible body. As the angels said, He will return ‘in like manner’ (Acts 1:11).\f*—\w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w who|strong="G3739"\w* preserves \w us|strong="G2249"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w* \w wrath|strong="G3709"\w*.\f + \fr 1:10 \ft Which expression of the Wrath is this? Jesus delivers us from the ultimate wrath, the Lake of fire, but based on 4:13-18 below I imagine that this refers to a pre-wrath Rapture.\f*   
\c 2  
\ms1 Paul's ministry in Thessalonica  
\m
\v 1 \w Now|strong="G1096"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G4771"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w*, brothers, \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w our|strong="G4314"\w* \w entrance|strong="G1529"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w did|strong="G1492"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w happen|strong="G1096"\w* \w without|strong="G3756"\w* purpose.  
\v 2 Rather, \w in|strong="G1722"\w* spite \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w already|strong="G4310"\w* \w suffered|strong="G4310"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* insulted \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Philippi|strong="G5375"\w*, \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w*, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w made|strong="G2316"\w* \w bold|strong="G3955"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* face \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w strong|strong="G2532"\w* opposition.\f + \fr 2:2 \ft They deliberately chose to pay a personal price to reach the Thessalonians. Are we prepared to do the same for the increase of Christ's Kingdom today?\f*  
\v 3 Further, \w our|strong="G1722"\w* \w exhortation|strong="G3874"\w* \w does|strong="G3761"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* spring \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w delusion|strong="G4106"\w* \w or|strong="G3761"\w* impurity, \w nor|strong="G3761"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w it|strong="G1063"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w deception|strong="G4106"\w*,  
\v 4 \w but|strong="G2316"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w* precisely \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \w been|strong="G3756"\w* \w approved|strong="G1381"\w* \w by|strong="G5259"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w to|strong="G3756"\w* \w be|strong="G3756"\w* \w entrusted|strong="G4100"\w* \w with|strong="G2980"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w*,\f + \fr 2:4 \ft They knew who they were and what they were about. They deny any form of delusion or hidden agenda—they were honest and aware. To be entrusted with the Gospel is a serious privilege.\f* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w so|strong="G3779"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w to|strong="G3756"\w* please \w men|strong="G3588"\w*, \w but|strong="G2316"\w* \w to|strong="G3756"\w* please \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* evaluates \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w hearts|strong="G2588"\w*.\f + \fr 2:4 \ft There it is: if you want to be a serious servant of God, His approval must be more important to you than that of the people around you.\f*  
\v 5 Further, \w you|strong="G1722"\w* \w well|strong="G1063"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G1096"\w* \w we|strong="G1063"\w* \w never|strong="G3777"\w* \w used|strong="G4218"\w* \w words|strong="G3056"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* flatter, \w or|strong="G3777"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* disguise \w greed|strong="G4124"\w* (\w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w is|strong="G2316"\w* \w witness|strong="G3144"\w*),  
\v 6 \w or|strong="G3777"\w* \w to|strong="G1410"\w* \w seek|strong="G2212"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w men|strong="G1722"\w* (whether \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w or|strong="G3777"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* others)\f + \fr 2:6 \ft Wow! If all Christian workers could say the same—no impurity, no deception, no flattery, no greed, no seeking glory—the church and the world would be different than they presently are.\f*—\w as|strong="G5613"\w* apostles \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*\f + \fr 2:6 \ft By his use of the plural, Paul is saying that Silvanus and Timothy were also apostles, presumably.\f* \w we|strong="G5613"\w* \w could|strong="G1410"\w* \w have|strong="G1510"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* ‘heavy’,  
\v 7 \w but|strong="G1437"\w* \w we|strong="G1437"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w gentle|strong="G2261"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, \w like|strong="G5613"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w nurse|strong="G5162"\w*\f + \fr 2:7 \ft The basic meaning of the noun is ‘nurse’, but the reference to ‘her own children’ has led some to translate it as ‘mother’. I take the point to be that whereas a professional nurse is supposed to take good care of anyone in her charge, she will be especially careful with her own children.\f* cherishing \w her|strong="G1437"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w children|strong="G5043"\w*.   
\s1 Paul's devotion to them  
\p
\v 8 Yearning \w over|strong="G1096"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w in|strong="G2532"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w* \w way|strong="G3779"\w*, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w* \w pleased|strong="G2106"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w share|strong="G3330"\w* \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w only|strong="G3440"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w selves|strong="G1438"\w*, \w because|strong="G1360"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w had|strong="G2532"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* dear \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w*.  
\v 9 \w Surely|strong="G3361"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w remember|strong="G3421"\w*, brothers, \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w toil|strong="G2873"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* exertion, \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w working|strong="G2038"\w* \w night|strong="G3571"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w as|strong="G1519"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w burden|strong="G1912"\w* \w any|strong="G5100"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*,\f + \fr 2:9 \ft It is clear that they supported themselves financially by working (making tents, or whatever). Between working, evangelizing and discipling (teaching), their sleeping time was probably short. So when could they be alone with God? In prison Paul had lots of time for contemplation (and writing letters), but not in Thessalonica. God places us in different situations at different times, and those situations place different demands upon us.\f* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w proclaimed|strong="G2784"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.   
\p
\v 10 \w You|strong="G5210"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w witnesses|strong="G3144"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w how|strong="G5613"\w* \w devoutly|strong="G3743"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w justly|strong="G1346"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* blamelessly \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w behaved|strong="G1096"\w* \w ourselves|strong="G1096"\w* \w among|strong="G1096"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*;  
\v 11 \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w know|strong="G1492"\w* \w how|strong="G5613"\w* \w we|strong="G2532"\w* treated \w each|strong="G1538"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w does|strong="G1492"\w* \w his|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w children|strong="G5043"\w*, \w exhorting|strong="G3870"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* comforting \w you|strong="G5210"\w*,  
\v 12 insisting \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w conduct|strong="G4043"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w manner|strong="G2316"\w* worthy \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w calls|strong="G2564"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* kingdom \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*.\f + \fr 2:12 \ft They really involved themselves in the lives of their converts, a deliberate (and costly) investment, that produced remarkable results. God is calling us into His Kingdom \+nd and\+nd* glory.\f*   
\s1 Their conversion  
\p
\v 13 \w Another|strong="G3739"\w* \w reason|strong="G1223"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w give|strong="G2168"\w* \w thanks|strong="G2168"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w continually|strong="G1223"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w when|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w received|strong="G1209"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* spoken \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w welcomed|strong="G1209"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w men|strong="G3778"\w* \w but|strong="G2532"\w*, \w as|strong="G2531"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w which|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w* operative \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w*.\f + \fr 2:13 \ft Whether written or spoken, any word from God is powerful, and changes lives.\f*  
\v 14 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*, brothers, \w became|strong="G1096"\w* \w imitators|strong="G3402"\w* \w of|strong="G5259"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*'s congregations \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w ones|strong="G3748"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Judea|strong="G2453"\w*,\f + \fr 2:14 \ft Israel was God's congregation, but not in Christ Jesus.\f* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w suffered|strong="G3958"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w same|strong="G2532"\w* \w things|strong="G3588"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w own|strong="G2398"\w* \w countrymen|strong="G4853"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w did|strong="G2532"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Jews|strong="G2453"\w*  
\v 15 (\w the|strong="G2532"\w* ones \w who|strong="G3588"\w* killed \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* own \w prophets|strong="G4396"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w persecuted|strong="G1559"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* please \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w hostile|strong="G1727"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* everybody,\f + \fr 2:15 \ft I take it that by “the Jews” Paul is referring to the leaders (John used the phrase in the same way).\f*  
\v 16 trying \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w prevent|strong="G2967"\w* \w us|strong="G1519"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w speaking|strong="G2980"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Gentiles|strong="G1484"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w they|strong="G1161"\w* \w may|strong="G2443"\w* \w be|strong="G1519"\w* \w saved|strong="G4982"\w*—\w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w as|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w fill|strong="G1519"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* measure \w of|strong="G1909"\w* \w their|strong="G1438"\w* sins. \w They|strong="G1161"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* received \w the|strong="G1519"\w* full impact \w of|strong="G1909"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Wrath|strong="G3709"\w*).\f + \fr 2:16 \ft I did the best I could with this last sentence, but the concept seems difficult. The verb is in the past and it is \+nd the\+nd* wrath (not just any old wrath). I get the impression that ‘the Jews’ described here had passed the point of no return (like Pharaoh and the plagues—at first he hardened his own heart, but after a while God hardened it and his doom was sealed) and were just making their accounting worse and worse, ‘filling up the measure’—from God's perspective the “full impact” had already been decreed. When someone passes the point of no return, Satan takes over, and they just get worse and worse. (If you think about it, you can probably come up with some examples.) 
\fp Ephesians 4:19 speaks of persons who ‘have abandoned themselves to depravity, greedily indulging in every kind of vileness’. And how should society defend itself against those who have ‘abandoned themselves to depravity’? The consequences of depravity always spill over into the surrounding society, and according to Psalm 5:5-6 the \+sc Lord\+sc* hates such people, and so presumably will not ‘draw’ them (John 6:44). 1 John 5:16-17 teaches that certain sinners are beyond the reach of prayer, they have passed the point of no return. If someone cannot be saved, then he needs to be neutralized (because of the harm he causes to others)—we need to ask God to teach us how to do this.\f*   
\ms1 Paul's concern for the Thessalonians  
\s1 A sense of bereavement  
\p
\v 17 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w*, brothers, having \w been|strong="G3756"\w* bereaved \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w for|strong="G4314"\w* \w a|strong="G1722"\w* \w short|strong="G3588"\w* \w season|strong="G2540"\w* (\w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w presence|strong="G4383"\w*, \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w heart|strong="G2588"\w*), \w made|strong="G3756"\w* \w every|strong="G1722"\w* \w effort|strong="G4704"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w your|strong="G3708"\w* \w face|strong="G4383"\w*, \w from|strong="G3756"\w* intense longing.\f + \fr 2:17 \ft I find the degree of emotional attachment described here to be surprising—perhaps a natural consequence of having poured himself into them as he did.\f*  
