\v 6 \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w no|strong="G3361"\w* \w one|strong="G3956"\w* trespass \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w defraud|strong="G4122"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* brother \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w matter|strong="G4229"\w*,\f + \fr 4:6 \ft I take it that this clause clarifies the interpretation of ‘vessel’; verse 4 refers to getting a wife. The term ‘defraud’ is quite strong, so I imagine it refers to courting (not to mention usurping) the affections of a girl already promised, if not betrothed, to another.\f* \w because|strong="G1360"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w avenger|strong="G1558"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w such|strong="G3778"\w* behavior,\f + \fr 4:6 \ft To behave so as to make yourself the object of God's vengeance does not sound like a good idea.\f* \w as|strong="G2531"\w*, \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w*, \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w have|strong="G2532"\w* already \w told|strong="G4302"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w warned|strong="G1263"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.  
